WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:10.160
Good afternoon and welcome to this afternoon's JPBM Communications Award lecture.

00:10.160 --> 00:13.880
I'm Michael Pearson with the Mathematical Association of America.

00:13.880 --> 00:20.320
We're part of JPBM and I'm really delighted to be able to recognize Grant Sanderson today

00:20.320 --> 00:23.920
with one of this year's communications awards.

00:23.920 --> 00:31.760
That is the creator and founder of Three Blue, One Brown, which is an effort to provide

00:31.760 --> 00:37.360
visualization of mathematics and it's a YouTube channel easily found.

00:37.360 --> 00:39.280
I hope you'll take a look at it.

00:39.280 --> 00:45.120
I had done my homework as I'm supposed to do when I was warned to do this and written

00:45.120 --> 00:50.760
out a nice introduction, which of course I can now not find on my electronic device,

00:50.760 --> 00:52.520
which is supposed to give me that.

00:52.520 --> 01:01.600
But I'll say, as I went on the site and as a harmonic analyst, I've spent a good bit

01:01.600 --> 01:07.240
of time thinking about convolutions, convolution kernels and so forth.

01:07.240 --> 01:12.840
I was really immediately attracted to see what Grant would do with convolution.

01:12.840 --> 01:15.000
He has a nice video presentation.

01:15.000 --> 01:19.040
What's the introduction to convolution?

01:19.040 --> 01:23.920
Some of you may know that the German word for convolution is Faltung, folding.

01:23.920 --> 01:29.320
And I think the video that Grant does with that really sort of makes that dynamic and

01:29.320 --> 01:33.280
shows you why folding is such a great word for convolution.

01:33.280 --> 01:37.200
So I encourage you to look at that one and any others that catch your eye.

01:37.200 --> 01:43.440
In any case, Grant graduated from Stanford University from Math and Computer Science in

01:43.440 --> 01:45.800
2015.

01:45.800 --> 01:52.560
He spent some time working on videos and instructional materials for the Khan Academy.

01:52.560 --> 01:58.040
And then by now, he's turned his full-time attention to three blue, one brown.

01:58.040 --> 02:00.440
And there's some really great stuff there.

02:00.440 --> 02:03.640
And without further ado, I'll let him tell us about it.

02:03.640 --> 02:05.640
Thank you.

02:05.640 --> 02:12.760
Thank you very much for that very warm introduction.

02:12.760 --> 02:16.360
I want to start just by saying a very heartfelt thanks to the members of the Joint Policy

02:16.360 --> 02:18.520
Board for the award.

02:18.520 --> 02:23.600
I will admit it is a little bit intimidating to receive an award for communication and then

02:23.600 --> 02:28.680
to be asked to immediately communicate to a roomful of people I have high respect for.

02:28.680 --> 02:33.040
I'll do my best, but I couldn't help but notice that a lot of the names on the list

02:33.040 --> 02:37.640
for this particular award in past years were just personal heroes of mine who served to

02:37.640 --> 02:40.360
inspire me a lot in getting started.

02:40.360 --> 02:43.760
Things like Steve Strogatz or James Glick or Matt Parker all come to mind, but those

02:43.760 --> 02:45.120
are just a few of very, very many.

02:45.120 --> 02:48.080
So I want to say thanks there.

02:48.080 --> 02:51.920
Broadly speaking, I want to talk about math communication itself and some of my thoughts

02:51.920 --> 02:53.520
around math communication.

02:53.520 --> 02:56.680
But this breaks into a number of different categories, and it's kind of a hard thing

02:56.680 --> 03:01.680
to think about as a unified whole because one component of that is education.

03:01.680 --> 03:06.400
And even that, it feels wrong to loop into a single group because education before university

03:06.400 --> 03:10.880
and math and education undergrad and on have a very qualitatively different flavor to them

03:10.880 --> 03:14.880
and how you might think about what approaches are best or what's the typical engagement

03:14.880 --> 03:17.040
a student has.

03:17.040 --> 03:20.680
And even that is very different from other forms of communication that happen, you know,

03:20.680 --> 03:25.120
presenting one's research or popularization, which is probably the bucket that I fit most

03:25.120 --> 03:30.760
closely into if I had to choose just one that's where I actually sit.

03:30.760 --> 03:34.640
But I do think it's very helpful, whichever one of these slices you find yourself in to

03:34.640 --> 03:40.000
think about them as intersecting each other and a lot of the value coming from that intersection.

03:40.000 --> 03:43.480
Some directions here are obvious, like if you're in education, it doesn't hurt to think

03:43.480 --> 03:45.840
about it as a popularization effort.

03:45.840 --> 03:48.680
If you want to popularize something, you try to make it more engaging.

03:48.680 --> 03:51.360
You try to connect to things that people are already interested in.

03:51.360 --> 03:54.160
It doesn't hurt to do the same if it's in a classroom.

03:54.160 --> 03:59.000
But I also think on the flip side, as someone who popularizes things or at least tries to,

03:59.000 --> 04:02.840
it's often not the right approach to do that head on and think, how can I make something

04:02.880 --> 04:06.960
that's going to reach the most people, you know, has the most click-baity title and the

04:06.960 --> 04:07.960
like.

04:07.960 --> 04:10.400
But what I've noticed is people just want to learn.

04:10.400 --> 04:14.360
The thing that makes something more popular, the thing that gets more reach, as often if

04:14.360 --> 04:18.840
I do something that's meant more as a classroom supplement, because people don't want to feel

04:18.840 --> 04:23.360
like they're just being watered down or talked down to, instead having a sense that what

04:23.360 --> 04:27.040
they're staring at is the authentic material, as if they were studying it and becoming an

04:27.040 --> 04:28.040
expert in it.

04:28.040 --> 04:30.440
I think that's a very inspiring feeling.

04:30.440 --> 04:35.000
So I titled this, Raising the Ceiling and Lowering the Floor of Math Exposition, referencing

04:35.000 --> 04:39.800
the fact that I think some of the efforts that we can make in trying to popularize it

04:39.800 --> 04:44.080
to reach more people can also make it more interesting to those who are already experts

04:44.080 --> 04:45.080
in it.

04:45.080 --> 04:50.600
But if I wanted to be a little bit more provocative in how I went about this talk, I could just

04:50.600 --> 04:56.360
as easily give what I have in mind the name of Math's Pedagogical Curse, because I really

04:56.360 --> 05:01.640
do think there's something strange going on with math, in particular, in contrast to

05:01.640 --> 05:07.400
some other fields, if we think about the perception that it has in the broader public.

05:07.400 --> 05:11.520
I think everybody in this room has probably had the experience of chatting with someone,

05:11.520 --> 05:13.400
cocktail party type environment.

05:13.400 --> 05:17.800
You mention you do something related to math, and the person says, as if there's no social

05:17.800 --> 05:21.600
taboo in saying it at all, which I guess there's not, oh, I'm not really a math person.

05:22.040 --> 05:26.880
Just fair, not everybody necessarily loves the subject that we do, but it's a funny phrase

05:26.880 --> 05:30.600
because you don't say that with respect to other things.

05:30.600 --> 05:33.720
But there's another turn of phrase that I've heard multiple different times, that in some

05:33.720 --> 05:40.400
sense is even more worrying than that one, which is the, I thought I liked math until.

05:40.400 --> 05:46.200
I have a very vivid memory, actually, of being a high school student touring different universities.

05:46.200 --> 05:48.680
And I was one of those students who always knew that I wanted to study math.

05:48.680 --> 05:50.520
I'd already fallen in love with it.

05:50.560 --> 05:53.840
So if I'd meet some students at the university, they asked their natural questions, oh, what

05:53.840 --> 05:55.040
do you think you might want to major in?

05:55.040 --> 05:57.800
I was like, I know, I want to major in math.

05:57.800 --> 06:00.920
And I remember this one student saying, oh, yeah, yeah, I thought I liked math.

06:00.920 --> 06:03.080
I even wanted to be a math major.

06:03.080 --> 06:07.280
And then I took a set theory class, and I discovered that I don't really like math, which is very

06:07.280 --> 06:08.280
sad.

06:08.280 --> 06:11.920
And I've heard variants of this through the years in various different contexts.

06:11.920 --> 06:14.960
Oh, I thought I liked math, and then I took a linear algebra class, right?

06:14.960 --> 06:19.120
I thought I liked math until, and then there's some point in which someone became disillusioned

06:19.120 --> 06:21.240
with it for whatever reason.

06:21.240 --> 06:25.640
Now that one feels like it's especially worth addressing, because it's very hard, I think,

06:25.640 --> 06:27.800
to ignite the light of interest in the first place.

06:27.800 --> 06:31.440
And even if maybe the more important one to address is the broad scope of people who don't

06:31.440 --> 06:36.160
self-identify as math people, we could just as easily ask, what are we doing wrong such

06:36.160 --> 06:39.920
that we get some people that thought they liked math and tell?

06:39.920 --> 06:42.800
Maybe the answer is math is just harder than other fields.

06:42.800 --> 06:48.400
It's just something you got to roll up your sleeves and work hard in order to attain, and

06:48.400 --> 06:50.560
not all people are willing to do that.

06:50.560 --> 06:53.440
I don't think that would be fair, though, because that kind of pushes the bump under

06:53.440 --> 06:56.960
the rug where you have to instead ask, does it have to be that hard?

06:56.960 --> 07:00.080
Is there anything that we're doing that makes it harder than it needs to be?

07:00.080 --> 07:05.120
And I have a little theory for at least one component of what might be going on with math

07:05.120 --> 07:08.000
in what makes it distinct from other fields.

07:08.000 --> 07:13.000
And it has to do, bear with me here, with the legend of King Midas.

07:13.000 --> 07:18.560
So for those of you who don't know, in Greek mythology, or it's one of those kind of intertwined

07:18.560 --> 07:22.880
with fake Greek history that Aristotle and the like would tell the people, you have this

07:22.880 --> 07:28.400
king supposedly who lived around the second millennium BC named Midas.

07:28.400 --> 07:33.480
And he does some good deeds that catch the attention of certain gods, and the god Dionysus

07:33.480 --> 07:36.920
says, I'm willing to give you a gift, name your gift, and I will give it to you.

07:36.920 --> 07:39.520
And Midas says, oh, well, what gift should I want?

07:39.520 --> 07:42.600
I think it would be great if anything that I touched could turn to gold.

07:42.600 --> 07:44.920
And Dionysus says, it is done.

07:44.920 --> 07:47.480
And Midas touches a twig, and it turns into gold.

07:47.480 --> 07:48.480
He's delighted.

07:48.480 --> 07:52.000
He goes back to his estate, and he starts touching all of the roses in his garden, and

07:52.000 --> 07:54.600
they turn into a beautiful metallic sheening gold.

07:54.600 --> 07:57.080
And he's just dreaming of all the wealth that he's going to have, and the wealth that his

07:57.080 --> 08:00.440
entire regime is going to have.

08:00.440 --> 08:05.040
And then when he gets to the banquet for dinner that night, he touches the chicken leg sitting

08:05.040 --> 08:08.440
in front of him, and it turns to gold, and it's completely inedible.

08:08.440 --> 08:12.040
Or in other tellings of the story, the moment that he realizes something might be a little

08:12.040 --> 08:17.400
bit wrong with this gift is when his daughter comes up to him, and he touches her, and she

08:17.400 --> 08:20.640
completely turns into gold, and he doesn't have her anymore.

08:20.640 --> 08:25.160
And of course, it precedes where it's a story of redemption and the like.

08:25.160 --> 08:31.760
But the gift that is analogous to this that I think math has, and it really is a gift,

08:31.760 --> 08:37.080
is a very special kind of exactness where we have the pleasure of knowing with 100 percent

08:37.440 --> 08:40.720
uncertainty if a conclusion follows from the premises.

08:40.720 --> 08:45.520
Maybe not 100 percent, it's subject to our ability to fall for certain logical fallacies

08:45.520 --> 08:47.560
or to miss holes in an argument.

08:47.560 --> 08:52.640
But with as much precision as you could possibly hope for, math has this kind of exactness.

08:52.640 --> 08:56.320
And a lot of other fields would just dream of anything like this.

08:56.320 --> 09:00.760
Hard sciences get kind of close if we think of physics or computer science.

09:00.760 --> 09:05.040
But even then, they're subject to a little bit of controversy with different ways you

09:05.040 --> 09:10.160
might interpret something, or even the best experiments aren't 100 percent precise.

09:10.160 --> 09:13.520
The softer sciences get even further away from this.

09:13.520 --> 09:17.600
Most forms of writing and discourse out there are more unabashedly subjective.

09:17.600 --> 09:22.440
You might think of art criticism, it's not unworthy, but it lacks this exactness.

09:22.440 --> 09:26.200
And the gift that comes from this exactness is that it helps you move forward a field.

09:26.200 --> 09:30.080
You don't fall into the same disputes that you might otherwise when there's room for

09:30.080 --> 09:33.920
ambiguity and misinterpretations.

09:33.920 --> 09:39.920
But I think what it might even mean for something to be mathematical is that it has this level

09:39.920 --> 09:40.920
of exactness.

09:40.920 --> 09:45.200
There's a friend of mine who's a biologist, and anytime we talk she always bemoans the

09:45.200 --> 09:49.120
fact that biology needs to become more of a mathematical science.

09:49.120 --> 09:54.200
Just how far could humanity progress if we could turn biology into a mathematical science.

09:54.200 --> 09:59.560
And presumably what she means by that is that you get a situation where you can draw conclusions

09:59.560 --> 10:04.000
from your premises with the same airtight rock solid rigor that a field like physics

10:04.000 --> 10:06.160
might have.

10:06.160 --> 10:10.080
The other really nice thing that this gets us, I think, is when you're writing something,

10:10.080 --> 10:14.520
like you're writing a textbook or a paper or a video or you're preparing a lecture,

10:14.520 --> 10:18.200
it gives a test for completion that no one else gets to have.

10:18.200 --> 10:21.320
We can have this clear notion of it's not done yet and then at some point there's a

10:21.320 --> 10:23.040
sense in which it's done.

10:23.040 --> 10:27.120
We can go through and you can make sure all of the definitions are completely unambiguous.

10:27.120 --> 10:29.240
We get to have unambiguous definitions.

10:29.240 --> 10:31.480
Nothing else doesn't get to have those.

10:31.480 --> 10:36.520
You can ask whether every object in the theorems that you reference have been previously defined.

10:36.520 --> 10:38.000
It's like a compiler checking code.

10:38.000 --> 10:41.720
You get to go through and the answer is either clearly delineated yes or clearly delineated

10:41.720 --> 10:42.720
no.

10:42.720 --> 10:46.400
And then most importantly for every claim that you make, you can ask was it completely

10:46.400 --> 10:47.640
justified.

10:47.640 --> 10:51.760
And then that constitutes a notion of explanation in some sense.

10:51.760 --> 10:56.640
It gives you a clear point where before you got to that point the paper wasn't finished

10:56.640 --> 10:59.920
or the lecture wasn't finished but after that point you can put a little bow around

10:59.920 --> 11:01.360
it and say it was finished.

11:01.360 --> 11:05.480
And like I said, I really do think it's a gift because it helps us move forward in a

11:05.480 --> 11:07.240
way that other fields can't.

11:07.240 --> 11:11.880
But there's a catch to this gift where in the same way that the things that King Minus

11:11.880 --> 11:15.520
might touch and turn to gold but this had a problem where he wouldn't be able to eat

11:15.520 --> 11:22.040
his food, the mathematician can touch anything, give it this notion of completely unambiguous

11:22.040 --> 11:23.040
rigor.

11:23.040 --> 11:28.880
But sometimes it runs the risk of leaving it, how shall we put it, slightly unpalatable

11:28.880 --> 11:33.880
to the average casual reader or maybe a little bit harder to consume than it needs to be

11:33.880 --> 11:35.880
for a typical student.

11:35.880 --> 11:41.360
And I do want to emphasize I don't think that it's a necessary thing that follows.

11:41.360 --> 11:45.080
I don't want to come across as implying that if something is rigorous that means that it's

11:45.080 --> 11:46.840
not clear.

11:46.840 --> 11:51.720
It's a little bit of an exaggeration to make the comparison with Midas quite like this.

11:51.720 --> 11:57.240
But what I do think is possibly the case is that this allure of such a notion of exactness

11:57.240 --> 12:01.040
where we can actually say that it is done in a certain sense means that rigor serves

12:01.040 --> 12:05.280
kind of as a distraction, right?

12:05.280 --> 12:09.120
I have to tell you, there will be no year that I grow tired of this meme.

12:09.120 --> 12:14.560
I know it's a little bit old, but the staying power with this is just unparalleled.

12:14.560 --> 12:20.760
No, but I think it's the case that a lot of really good authors manage to achieve both

12:20.800 --> 12:21.960
rigor and clarity.

12:21.960 --> 12:25.520
And in fact, the point of rigor is often to add more clarity.

12:25.520 --> 12:30.320
But the thing that I suspect might happen every now and then is that because the rigor

12:30.320 --> 12:35.120
gives you this very clean, nice thing to think about and because thinking about pedagogical

12:35.120 --> 12:39.760
clarity is a lot messier, you know, it's harder to define, you can't put a bow around it.

12:39.760 --> 12:44.440
There's not one point when you've gone from not done to completely done that after scratching

12:44.440 --> 12:47.920
the itch of knowing that something's been written completely rigorously, it's easy to

12:47.920 --> 12:51.240
call a work done when maybe we shouldn't call it done yet.

12:51.240 --> 12:55.520
And there's context where this is maybe okay, research papers come to mind, but in things

12:55.520 --> 13:00.840
that are more explicitly pedagogical, textbooks come to mind, I would propose that maybe it

13:00.840 --> 13:06.640
makes sense to invite into the culture a similar focus that we already have on the rigor of

13:06.640 --> 13:10.360
it, but instead onto something for the pedagogical clarity.

13:10.360 --> 13:15.200
And I'll give an example here, which is essentially just from the book that was sitting on my

13:15.200 --> 13:17.600
desk while I was putting together these slides.

13:17.600 --> 13:22.240
I actually love the textbook, it's really great and one of the only reasons I feel comfortable

13:22.240 --> 13:26.000
highlighting it and poking a little bit of fun at one of the sections is because it otherwise

13:26.000 --> 13:30.120
holds up very well and it's one I would unabashedly recommend.

13:30.120 --> 13:35.640
But I was thinking, okay, you know, how well does the author tend to think about points

13:35.640 --> 13:39.760
of pedagogical clarity in addition to points of rigorous clarity?

13:39.760 --> 13:43.120
And one particular section that I was looking at was about something called the Poisson

13:43.120 --> 13:47.400
summation formula, many of you might be familiar with it, it essentially says for a function

13:47.400 --> 13:52.560
which is sufficiently nice, if you add up the value of that function across all of the

13:52.560 --> 13:57.960
integers, it gets the same thing as if you add up the Fourier transform of that function

13:57.960 --> 13:58.960
across all the integers.

13:58.960 --> 14:03.120
It's kind of a wild formula, very useful in many different contexts.

14:03.120 --> 14:07.720
And the proof that the book gives is actually really beautiful, I liked it a lot.

14:07.720 --> 14:13.600
It starts off by describing a certain function a little bit out of the blue, but if you look

14:13.640 --> 14:20.400
at it, you notice that it has poles at all of the integers and the residue at those poles

14:20.400 --> 14:24.960
are exactly the values that you might want to sum on the left hand side of your formula.

14:24.960 --> 14:30.000
And essentially what the book does is it kind of after handing down this construct and after

14:30.000 --> 14:34.200
describing a certain contour that you might integrate along, and the context here was,

14:34.200 --> 14:38.320
you know, it's in a setting of assuming people are familiar with the complex analysis up

14:38.320 --> 14:42.160
to the point in the book and know about contour, integrals, and the like, it goes through and

14:42.200 --> 14:46.400
shows how you can have a very elegant derivation of the formula basically by unpacking what

14:46.400 --> 14:50.920
this integral is saying and step by step, it eventually turns it into the sum on the

14:50.920 --> 14:52.440
right hand side.

14:52.440 --> 14:56.200
So it's very beautiful, it involves a lot of clever ideas, things fit together nicely

14:56.200 --> 15:01.440
at the end, you can look back on it and I think as a writer, think what more could you

15:01.440 --> 15:03.880
possibly want?

15:03.880 --> 15:06.160
It's as clean a proof as I could imagine.

15:06.160 --> 15:10.520
And I think there's a culture in math textbooks that sort of says once something is proven,

15:10.520 --> 15:12.480
that means it is complete.

15:12.480 --> 15:18.800
But if you try to add a secondary checklist that says what are the pedagogical considerations,

15:18.800 --> 15:22.000
even though I think this is a great book, and even though I think the proof has a lot

15:22.000 --> 15:25.640
of staying power, there are dozens of other questions that I could think one might want

15:25.640 --> 15:30.440
to lead up to this particular fact with or follow it with.

15:30.440 --> 15:33.800
You know, to start off with, you could just say, what is this formula, how do you think

15:33.800 --> 15:37.600
about it, why should you expect that something like this would be true, what are the circumstances

15:37.600 --> 15:41.080
that you might run into in the mathematical wild, where you would think that this is something

15:41.080 --> 15:43.280
that you need to bring to bear.

15:43.280 --> 15:48.240
For example, it doesn't hurt to illustrate just a little bit, like how do we parse what

15:48.240 --> 15:49.560
each side is saying.

15:49.560 --> 15:53.160
The left hand side, which is adding up the value of the function for all of the positive

15:53.160 --> 15:59.080
integers, you could kind of think of as a extremely coarse Riemann sum for the whole

15:59.080 --> 16:00.240
function.

16:00.240 --> 16:05.560
And one of the terms on the right hand side, if you take the Fourier transform just at

16:05.560 --> 16:09.880
zero, those of you who are comfortable with the matter know that that's just the same

16:09.880 --> 16:12.440
thing as integrating the function.

16:12.440 --> 16:17.320
And so what that tells you is that much of the left hand side is already encapsulated

16:17.320 --> 16:20.840
just with the zero term on the right hand side, and you know, the student might then

16:20.840 --> 16:25.080
be invited to think about how all of the other Fourier coefficients give you a sort of correction

16:25.080 --> 16:30.640
factor between the difference of this coarse Riemann sum in the area, and that instills

16:30.640 --> 16:35.000
a little bit of intuition around if you have an especially smooth function, one that stays

16:35.000 --> 16:38.960
very flat, that that would suggest that less correction is needed in comparison to if it

16:38.960 --> 16:40.800
has high variation.

16:40.800 --> 16:44.160
When it comes to the proof itself, while the author gave a delightful proof, there were

16:44.160 --> 16:47.800
many steps where, like I said, it felt like it was handed down from on high, and what

16:47.800 --> 16:51.280
I would love to see or would love to feel is a sense of how I might have discovered

16:51.280 --> 16:52.280
that myself.

16:52.280 --> 16:56.520
I think it's hard to understand just how delightful it can be if you as the reader feel like the

16:56.520 --> 17:01.320
thing that was coming in is something that you kind of anticipated and that it's validating

17:01.320 --> 17:06.080
rather than feeling like you're the one who has to kind of validate that the monument

17:06.080 --> 17:09.120
that you were handed does the thing that's being claimed.

17:09.120 --> 17:13.480
And in this case, you know, I think there's a longer description, but length isn't necessarily

17:13.480 --> 17:17.920
the enemy, that could provide a sort of path of rediscovery for the very elegant proof

17:17.920 --> 17:21.440
that potentially could give it even more staying power.

17:21.440 --> 17:27.240
Now, what I mainly want to ask through the remainder of this talk is, in light of the

17:27.240 --> 17:32.280
fact that we have such a satisfying checklist for rigor that really distinguishes math in

