of what does it mean for my piece to even be done, I think can help force that to come

34:30.340 --> 34:32.500
about a little bit more.

34:32.500 --> 34:37.020
Now the next thing that I like to think about, and this is one where, by the way, every single

34:37.020 --> 34:41.500
time I do a first draft of something, I violate the principle that I'm about to describe and

34:41.540 --> 34:44.300
I have to go and realize, oh, wait, no, I should apply this principle.

34:44.300 --> 34:47.940
There's something bizarrely unnatural about it, but I really do think it helps to make

34:47.940 --> 34:48.940
things clearer.

34:48.940 --> 34:53.580
To illustrate it, I'm going to talk about a much simpler piece of math, and instead of

34:53.580 --> 34:58.180
doing zeta function type stuff, we're going to go to simple algebra, and I mean like normal

34:58.180 --> 35:01.780
high school, middle school algebra, not abstract.

35:01.780 --> 35:05.340
And I want you to kind of put yourself back in the state of mind whenever it is the case

35:05.340 --> 35:10.740
that you were first learning, just basic algebra, whatever age you were, whatever class you

35:10.780 --> 35:16.580
might have been in, and I'm going to paint two potential classes, and I want you to just

35:16.580 --> 35:22.140
think about how much does each of those classes resonate with this imagined past version of

35:22.140 --> 35:25.540
yourself that's sitting there learning it for the first time.

35:25.540 --> 35:28.620
So the way that class A proceeds is like this.

35:28.620 --> 35:33.620
The teacher starts by asking all of the students, can anyone factor the number 35 for me?

35:33.620 --> 35:36.980
And actually, I'll do this, why not, anyone in the audience, you want to shout out the

35:37.020 --> 35:39.020
factors of 35?

35:39.020 --> 35:41.820
Five and seven, excellent.

35:41.820 --> 35:47.820
Now, the teacher then asks the students, can anyone please factor the number 143 for me?

35:47.820 --> 35:53.820
So, because this is a room full of mathematicians, everyone immediately shouts 11 times 13, which

35:53.820 --> 35:57.380
is fun, but the students, you know, maybe they think about it a little bit more, they

35:57.380 --> 36:01.340
check whether various numbers go into it, and the one that does their little long division

36:01.340 --> 36:04.660
with the 11, they raise their hand with a little bit more time than this crowd would

36:04.660 --> 36:06.500
and says 11 times 13.

36:06.500 --> 36:10.820
So then the teacher asks, can anyone factor 3599?

36:10.820 --> 36:18.740
Now this is a fun room to do it in, so 59 times 61, great.

36:18.740 --> 36:23.380
This does not happen in middle schools.

36:23.380 --> 36:29.980
Although I was recently doing something where I brought up this example in a room full of

36:29.980 --> 36:34.380
high schoolers and there was one student who said it, he said the answer, he said it's

36:34.500 --> 36:41.500
59 times 61, and there was an audible gasp from the whole room, because it's absurd if

36:41.700 --> 36:43.820
you think about it factoring the normal way.

36:43.820 --> 36:46.780
But the teacher says, you know, there's a reason that I led into it the way that I did,

36:46.780 --> 36:51.220
and the teacher invites the students to think about how 35 is very close to a square number,

36:51.220 --> 36:54.900
it's so close to something round, it's close to six times six, and it maybe doesn't feel

36:54.900 --> 36:58.700
like a coincidence that the two factors are also close to six.

36:58.700 --> 37:02.740
It looks kind of like six times six, but you just nudged one up, you nudged one down.

37:02.780 --> 37:08.540
Similarly, 143, it's very close, it's just one less than a square number, namely 12 times 12,

37:08.540 --> 37:11.580
and it's not a coincidence that the factors, if you kind of squint your eyes, also look

37:11.580 --> 37:12.780
like 12 times 12.

37:12.780 --> 37:17.660
So if you're just pattern matching, then you might guess that the factor should look something

37:17.660 --> 37:21.380
like 60 times something like 60, and if it followed the same exact pattern, it would be

37:21.380 --> 37:23.220
one more and one less.

37:23.220 --> 37:28.140
And, you know, the teacher wants, they can go through a couple other examples like this,

37:28.140 --> 37:32.260
start to convince the class that maybe, just maybe, this kind of wild fact is true,

37:32.260 --> 37:36.660
and it lets you look like that person who can receive an audible gas from all

37:36.660 --> 37:39.620
of your classmates for being able to factor a number, which is very fun.

37:39.620 --> 37:43.980
And then the teacher can draw out a diagram to help explain what's going on,

37:43.980 --> 37:48.660
where if you imagine, you know, what does a square number mean, like six squared in this case,

37:48.660 --> 37:52.660
you might imagine six by six boxes, and if we subtract one, you're kind of kicking one

37:52.660 --> 37:56.620
off of the corner, and if you rearrange this a little bit, what it means to try

37:56.620 --> 38:00.900
to factor the number is to try to arrange all of your boxes into some kind of rectangle.

38:00.900 --> 38:04.100
And in this case, we can do that where one of the rectangles has a width that's just

38:04.100 --> 38:08.100
one bigger and, or the rectangle has a width that's one bigger and then a height that's

38:08.100 --> 38:09.980
one smaller.

38:09.980 --> 38:13.580
And you can actually generalize this, if instead of kicking off a corner that was just a little

38:13.580 --> 38:19.300
one by one square, if you kicked off a y by y square, you can basically play the same

38:19.300 --> 38:22.620
game to factor it to look like x plus y times x minus y.

38:22.620 --> 38:26.460
And it's very fun, again, this gives you a lot of fun mental math tricks, where you

38:26.460 --> 38:30.740
can say things that make you seem like a genius, where someone can say factor the number

38:30.740 --> 38:36.700
at 9,991, and you can do it without a calculator, or on the flip side, it's a nice trick for

38:36.700 --> 38:41.420
multiplying certain numbers, assuming that you know the square of what sits halfway in

38:41.420 --> 38:43.180
between them.

38:43.180 --> 38:48.180
So that's class A. Class B starts off by saying, hello class, today we're going to be studying

38:48.180 --> 38:49.660
the difference of squares formula.

38:49.660 --> 38:53.620
The difference of squares formula states that if we take x squared minus y squared, this

38:53.620 --> 38:57.140
can be factored into x plus y multiplied by x minus y.

38:57.140 --> 39:00.820
The formula is very easy, it's not too hard to show, because if we expand out the right

39:00.820 --> 39:06.900
hand side, you see that you have x squared, we subtract off yx, we add y times x, so those

39:06.900 --> 39:09.980
two cancel out, and we get y squared.

39:09.980 --> 39:12.500
The instruction really doesn't take long.

39:12.500 --> 39:16.380
You can give an example, like if you plug in 1, it gives a nice fact that you can factor

39:16.380 --> 39:19.500
something into x plus 1 and x minus 1.

39:19.500 --> 39:23.380
And then there's a worksheet that you can kind of work through, which is, this is just

39:23.380 --> 39:27.460
a worksheet that I found when I was looking for classes on difference of squares formula.

39:27.460 --> 39:32.500
Now, okay, maybe I'm being a little bit unfair, not giving enough personality to the second

39:32.500 --> 39:34.220
lesson as I could have.

39:34.220 --> 39:39.140
But broadly speaking, if we try to compare what's going on with these two, class B does

39:39.140 --> 39:43.580
something which is so tempting to do in so many other contexts in math, which is that

39:43.580 --> 39:45.940
you start with the most powerful thing.

39:45.940 --> 39:48.820
You state what the powerful thing is that you're going to do.

39:48.820 --> 39:50.980
Usually that takes the form of an abstraction.

39:50.980 --> 39:53.700
It's the most true thing.

39:53.700 --> 39:55.540
It's kind of easier to show in that case.

39:55.540 --> 39:59.300
This is part of what we love about abstraction, is that it's just a lot quicker to verify

39:59.300 --> 40:04.620
that that's true than it is to try to come up with some reason why a numerical case where

40:04.620 --> 40:08.620
you're gathering around a bunch of squares or stones or whatever you're using to concretize

40:08.620 --> 40:09.620
it.

40:09.620 --> 40:13.980
And even then, the reasoning doesn't cover all the general cases necessarily, because

40:13.980 --> 40:15.820
you'd say, well, does it have to be an integer?

40:15.820 --> 40:17.180
Would this work with negative numbers?

40:17.180 --> 40:20.420
And would it work with complex numbers, all of that?

40:20.420 --> 40:26.180
So that's the temptation of class B. Class A teaches using data and examples.

40:26.180 --> 40:29.740
And it's not that the abstraction isn't a goal, it is the goal.

40:29.740 --> 40:31.500
That's the function of the lesson at the end.

40:31.500 --> 40:35.140
And it's not that you want to encourage students every single time that they come across the

40:35.140 --> 40:39.380
difference of squares formula to picture in their head a little grid of x by x and y, because

40:39.380 --> 40:42.660
sometimes you're just in the middle of doing a bunch of other algebra, and the whole point

40:42.660 --> 40:47.500
of abstraction is that you don't have to think about that and you can do it more quickly.

40:47.500 --> 40:51.420
But I think for the first time that you're seeing it, if you really want it to land inside

40:51.420 --> 40:56.980
yourself, it's more helpful to kind of think in terms of layers of abstraction where before

40:56.980 --> 41:01.380
getting to the lesson you have in mind, shift yourself one abstraction layer lower.

41:01.380 --> 41:05.300
Instead of, in this case, thinking about variables and letters, think about numbers.

41:05.300 --> 41:08.600
And then if you show lots of different examples with those numbers, it's kind of like light

41:08.600 --> 41:12.060
bulbs in the mind of the student that are thinking of all those examples.

41:12.060 --> 41:16.540
And if there's a certain ineffable character that connects them, the student can kind of

41:16.580 --> 41:20.620
think about the things that connect them, the fact that things feel close to squares,

41:20.620 --> 41:26.420
or that the two factors that you got are suspiciously close to the square root of the relevant number.

41:26.420 --> 41:30.380
And when we did the diagram, in a sense that's an abstraction layer even lower, where instead

41:30.380 --> 41:35.260
of thinking of numbers and numerals representing amounts, you're just looking at the amounts

41:35.260 --> 41:38.860
and you can see the connection between the numerical facts that got you to feel like

41:38.860 --> 41:41.780
a wizard and something more direct with those amounts.

41:41.780 --> 41:46.220
And by the time you get to the abstraction, it feels so cool and so powerful because you

41:46.260 --> 41:49.620
have a sense for all of the different things underneath that it's touching, all of the

41:49.620 --> 41:55.340
different mental math tricks that are encapsulated in such a beautiful and concise formula.

41:55.340 --> 41:59.700
It seems a little banal to those of us once you're comfortable with algebra because it's

41:59.700 --> 42:01.940
just one identity out of many.

42:01.940 --> 42:06.780
But I think reminding students that every identity that you see in algebra kind of encapsulates

42:06.780 --> 42:12.020
this whole body of potential mental math tricks or potential statements about a wide variety

42:12.020 --> 42:13.940
of little diagrams you could draw out.

42:13.980 --> 42:18.060
There's something about that that feels very inspiring, to me at least.

42:18.060 --> 42:22.820
Now class B in contrast, it teaches the same topic.

42:22.820 --> 42:28.540
It gives you the same ultimate fact and assuming the students remember the fact, I can't imagine

42:28.540 --> 42:34.700
that they would test much more poorly, at least if you do the test with this kind of

42:34.700 --> 42:38.060
worksheet that they got their practice on shortly after the lesson.

42:38.060 --> 42:41.380
I might question whether they remember the formula as well if you ask them five years

42:41.420 --> 42:46.020
later or something like that, but if I'm trying to picture what's going on in the kind of

42:46.020 --> 42:50.020
depiction of, this isn't literally what's happening in the brain, but you know my schematic

42:50.020 --> 42:54.260
for layers of abstraction in the brain, you're just sort of lighting up the one bulb you

42:54.260 --> 42:58.220
care about and it's not sitting on something else to support it, it hasn't been brought

42:58.220 --> 42:59.220
about.

42:59.220 --> 43:02.300
There wasn't a sense that it was answering a question or articulating a pattern that

43:02.300 --> 43:04.580
already existed in someone's mind.

43:04.580 --> 43:09.260
So this is a thing I like to think about as much as I can where if there's a given topic,

43:09.260 --> 43:13.140
I try to draw out what are the relevant layers of abstraction at play here.

43:13.140 --> 43:17.380
Now there's not like a universal hierarchy or something like that, but just as an example

43:17.380 --> 43:21.460
for what that might look like, at the bottom most layer we have things like quantities.

43:21.460 --> 43:25.180
One of the very first things we do when we're teaching students math is to get them to go

43:25.180 --> 43:30.620
from feeling comfortable with quantities to thinking comfortably with numerals and eventually

43:30.620 --> 43:32.500
everyone gains a certain fluency with this.

43:32.500 --> 43:35.500
Maybe there's a couple bumps in the road while they're learning about fractions and doing

43:35.500 --> 43:38.940
that, but by and large everyone kind of gets that layer of abstraction.

43:38.940 --> 43:42.380
And then similarly at some point instead of talking about numerals, we realize that there's

43:42.380 --> 43:46.980
just a lot of facts that are nicer and encapsulated with algebra and symbols and can you just

43:46.980 --> 43:50.660
communicate more, you can think more quickly with respect to certain things and it's such

43:50.660 --> 43:53.420
a powerful tool.

43:53.420 --> 43:58.260
The next layer, it's not exactly the case that functions abstract the notion of algebra,

43:58.260 --> 44:03.220
but kind of it's the case that certain, let's say, facts and calculus that you're learning,

44:03.220 --> 44:07.180
you draw out with respect to functions where every instantiation of that function that might

44:07.180 --> 44:12.780
come along looks like either algebra or some bit of trigonometry or something there.

44:12.780 --> 44:16.740
And so you write out your facts about derivatives and integrals and chain rule and the like,

44:16.740 --> 44:22.940
not with respect to specific functions, but instead just in a more abstract setting.

44:22.940 --> 44:26.740
And again the next layer is maybe a little bit silly to think of as like a definitive

44:26.740 --> 44:32.940
canonical one, but there's a sense in which functions are a single instance of function

44:32.940 --> 44:36.740
spaces at least, like a collection of functions, an instance of vector spaces.

44:36.780 --> 44:41.100
And a lot of the facts that you might have around functions can fit into a more general

44:41.100 --> 44:44.500
framework where things like the derivative and the integral you can think of in terms

44:44.500 --> 44:46.700
of linear mappings and the like.

44:46.700 --> 44:50.420
And of course you keep going on and on and on until people get talking to you about higher

44:50.420 --> 44:53.620
categories and it's just a snake that eats its own tail up there.

44:53.620 --> 44:58.540
But the point is that whatever layer you're sitting on here, you know, I give an example

44:58.540 --> 45:03.780
in a low set of those layers between numerals and algebra, but I think even at higher layers,

45:03.820 --> 45:08.900
I just personally think that it's very helpful for the first time that a student sees something

45:08.900 --> 45:14.820
to populate their mind with data of a lower layer before you articulate the higher layer,

45:14.820 --> 45:16.900
even if the goal is the higher layer.

45:16.900 --> 45:21.180
So if you're teaching linear algebra, for example, even though the whole beauty of linear

45:21.180 --> 45:26.700
algebra is the generality, the fact that it's not just describing R2 and R3 and the like,

45:26.700 --> 45:30.420
but that there's a whole body of things that you can model with vector spaces and then use

45:30.460 --> 45:35.380
facts that you've derived very rigorously just from the axioms to come to conclusions about

45:35.380 --> 45:37.540
all the different things that could be vector spaces.

45:37.540 --> 45:43.300
Nevertheless, the intuition building phase is probably best done if you populate it with

45:43.300 --> 45:44.300
a bunch of examples.

45:44.300 --> 45:49.700
Maybe it's good to spread out not just from R2 and R3, but certain other examples of more

45:49.700 --> 45:54.420
playful, you know, vector spaces that one might come up with.

45:54.420 --> 45:58.420
I think one example that comes to mind is just an excellent example to get someone starting

45:58.420 --> 46:03.300
to think about more abstract vector spaces is magic squares.

46:03.300 --> 46:06.820
And if you teach them the notion of a three-by-three magic square, where all of the columns and

46:06.820 --> 46:12.060
rows and such have to add up to a certain amount, you then ask someone how many dimensions

46:12.060 --> 46:16.820
is the space of all magic squares and what's the basis for the magic squares.

46:16.820 --> 46:19.940
And that kind of question can get them thinking, again, it's very concrete.

46:19.940 --> 46:25.460
It's a specific instance, a very specific kind of vector space, but that starts to invite

46:25.500 --> 46:31.300
them to think about what's common across the arrows drawn in 2D space examples that they

46:31.300 --> 46:33.800
might have cut their teeth on earlier.

46:33.800 --> 46:38.660
So with my checklist, I think what this means is I try to ask, are abstractions preceded

46:38.660 --> 46:39.660
with concrete examples?

46:39.660 --> 46:45.100
And like I said, for whatever reason, this is one that the first draft, if I write something,

46:45.100 --> 46:46.380
just doesn't do it.

46:46.380 --> 46:50.740
And I think it's because once you understand something, the way you think about it, at

46:50.740 --> 46:54.460
least the way I think about it, tends to be from the abstraction down, it's frankly

46:54.460 --> 46:58.500
a lot easier to think about the difference of squares formula algebraically than it is

46:58.500 --> 47:03.100
to try to think about a bunch of mental math tricks or a grid of squares or anything like

47:03.100 --> 47:04.100
that.

47:04.100 --> 47:05.420
It's just so quick to verify.

47:05.420 --> 47:08.940
And then this goes for a lot of other things where the reason we do the abstractions is

47:08.940 --> 47:12.540
because it allows for more mental fluency, but then that often can give us a mistake

47:12.540 --> 47:17.700
that it means as you're divulging the topic, the thing that is easiest for you, the expert,

47:17.700 --> 47:21.940
is necessarily the thing that is most conducive to a new learner coming in.

47:21.940 --> 47:26.740
And so by specifically writing it out and letting it be one of the checks, I think it

47:26.740 --> 47:29.900
can shift my lessons, hopefully, to be the better.

47:29.900 --> 47:34.700
Now the last one I'd like to talk about is actually something I've only more recently

47:34.700 --> 47:35.820
started thinking about.

47:35.820 --> 47:41.940
And it's hard to do in videos, and I'm curious about if there's ways to kind of do it better.

47:41.940 --> 47:43.940
It's definitely applicable in classrooms.

47:43.940 --> 47:48.260
I think done with good writing, it's applicable in textbooks.

47:48.260 --> 47:52.180
But one nice thing to illustrate it is a certain study by Manu Kapoor.

47:52.180 --> 47:56.100
He even gave a certain TED talk about studies like this.

47:56.100 --> 48:00.860
But the one that caught my eye is this paper called Productive Failure in Learning Math.

48:00.860 --> 48:04.740
And he focuses on the nature of failure, but to my mind, that's not even the most interesting

48:04.740 --> 48:05.740
part.

48:05.740 --> 48:11.420
The neat thing here is he has two different classes that he teaches or that in the experiment

48:11.420 --> 48:16.060
are taught to a group of middle school students, and the middle school students are segregated

48:16.060 --> 48:20.300
into two different groups in class A. They experience two hours.

48:20.300 --> 48:24.620
One is an instruction phase and following that is a problem-solving phase, and the only

48:24.620 --> 48:28.300
difference with the second class, the only difference is that they flip the order.

48:28.300 --> 48:32.500
They did a one-hour problem-solving phase followed by the instruction phase.

48:32.500 --> 48:35.980
And the example matters here because I don't think you can do this for any kind of problem

48:35.980 --> 48:41.820
solving, but it was a well-chosen problem-solving prompt in the case of this class because they

48:41.820 --> 48:44.780
were teaching the idea of standard deviation.

48:44.820 --> 48:48.820
And the question that they asked was to present the students with two different basketball

48:48.820 --> 48:53.020
players and they give a whole bunch of data over the course of a season of basketball

48:53.020 --> 48:56.340
for how many points each one of those players scored.

48:56.340 --> 49:00.020
And they were told, Mike and Dave are two basketball players, and an award has to be

49:00.020 --> 49:05.820
given to the most consistent player of the two, and the decision has to be made mathematically.

49:05.820 --> 49:10.380
And so the students were invited to design as many measures of consistency as they could

49:10.380 --> 49:12.500
to determine which of those players is more consistent.

49:13.140 --> 49:17.980
It's a very fun exercise, actually, and so the middle schoolers were given 60 minutes

49:17.980 --> 49:21.620
to think about this, to look over the data, try to add some things up, use their calculators

49:21.620 --> 49:25.100
that they could, come up with some measure of consistency.

49:25.100 --> 49:27.220
And a couple things came out of it.

49:27.220 --> 49:31.420
One of them is that the students in that second one that did the problem-solving phase before

49:31.420 --> 49:35.780
they did the instruction, they reported that the instruction phase was harder, that they

49:35.780 --> 49:37.860
were spending more mental energy on it.

49:38.580 --> 49:44.180
Now another relevant thing is the number of tactics they came up with, it was a lot higher.

49:44.180 --> 49:48.460
There was a lot more variation in the measures of consistency they came up with when they

49:48.460 --> 49:50.380
hadn't been taught the proper lesson yet.

49:50.380 --> 49:54.820
But the most interesting thing, to me at least, is when they did a post-test on all

49:54.820 --> 49:58.900
of this, and they had just questions trying to measure how well the students understood

49:58.900 --> 50:01.100
the topic of standard deviation.

50:01.100 --> 50:04.860
The questions broke into various different categories, so the ones that were categorized

50:04.860 --> 50:09.140
as procedural knowledge, just, are you able to carry out the computation and all that,

50:09.140 --> 50:12.660
there wasn't really much of a difference between the two camps.

50:12.660 --> 50:17.300
But the ones that the researchers marked as measuring conceptual understanding, it was

50:17.300 --> 50:21.860
like two standard deviations higher in conceptual understanding that the second group had compared

50:21.860 --> 50:23.620
to the first.

50:23.620 --> 50:27.980
And then questions that were marked as measuring how transferrable the knowledge was, were they

50:27.980 --> 50:32.420
able to transfer it to a different context, it was like one standard deviation higher.

50:32.420 --> 50:35.740
And on the one hand, kind of always have to take a little bit of grain of salt with

50:35.740 --> 50:39.980
education studies, and especially if they're small sample sizes and things like that.

50:39.980 --> 50:45.900
But to me at least, this one rings very true, the idea that if you seriously engage with

50:45.900 --> 50:50.860
a problem before you're told the answer, that that actually makes you engage more meaningfully

50:50.860 --> 50:54.060
with the answer once it's told to you in the instruction.

50:54.060 --> 50:57.540
So I think probably a lot of people in this room have had the experience of toying over

50:57.540 --> 51:01.860
some problem, not because it was assigned for homework after a given class was given,

51:01.860 --> 51:04.860
but because for whatever reason, you just were interested in that problem.

51:04.860 --> 51:08.420
And then maybe a little bit later, maybe a couple years later, you come across someone

51:08.420 --> 51:12.020
who's answering that problem, they happen to articulate exactly the thing you were looking

51:12.020 --> 51:13.020
for.

51:13.020 --> 51:17.340
In my experience, that answer sticks so much better than the answers that are given for

51:17.340 --> 51:21.460
questions that I hadn't yet been thinking about or toiling over.

51:21.460 --> 51:27.660
So the third thing that I put on this checklist is, does the lesson start with some kind of

51:27.660 --> 51:29.460
motivating question?

51:29.460 --> 51:33.820
Like I said, I think that's kind of hard to do with video because you have to invite

51:33.820 --> 51:38.420
the audience to pause and think about it, which some people will do, and that's great.

51:38.420 --> 51:42.340
But realistically, a lot of people are a little bit more passive in that moment.

51:42.340 --> 51:46.700
So it seems like something that's much better done in conjunction with instruction, whether

51:46.700 --> 51:51.540
that instruction comes in the form of a video or a textbook or something like that.

51:51.540 --> 51:55.820
I think a good author with a textbook can kind of do a lot too, at the very least, proceed

51:55.820 --> 52:02.780
the relevant sections with the right questions, maybe even give some stern suggestions to

52:02.780 --> 52:04.340
the reader that, no, really, stop.

52:04.340 --> 52:05.340
Think about this.

52:05.340 --> 52:08.420
If you really want to engage with it, if you really want to remember it, take five minutes

52:08.420 --> 52:11.700
to close the book and think about this question.

52:11.700 --> 52:15.260
But whatever form it takes, I think when the student has actually engaged with something

52:15.260 --> 52:19.420
like this, it stands to make the instruction itself land a lot more.

52:19.420 --> 52:23.100
And it's not something I've always done, so that's a thing I've been thinking about

52:23.100 --> 52:26.060
more and how I can bring that into the future.

52:26.060 --> 52:30.380
So I'm curious, actually, what other people would add to this list and what principles

52:30.380 --> 52:33.940
they have for a checklist of pedagogy.

52:33.940 --> 52:37.740
And just to reiterate the point, I do think that the reason that it's important to have

52:37.740 --> 52:42.940
something like this, rather than just letting it be subjective and fuzzy, is because those

52:42.940 --> 52:47.660
of us who are mathematically interested, we have a kind of attraction to the definite

52:47.700 --> 52:54.940
and the allure of something that's like exact in the sense that rigor is exact, is so tempting

52:54.940 --> 52:58.660
that it can sometimes mean we lose sight of the other forms of completion that are just

52:58.660 --> 52:59.900
as worthy.

52:59.900 --> 53:04.260
And I also want to reiterate, it's not a statement that rigor and clarity necessarily

53:04.260 --> 53:05.700
sit in contrast with each other.

53:05.700 --> 53:08.980
The best author is definitely achieved both at the same time.

53:08.980 --> 53:14.180
It's just when we care about something like clarity with the same verb that we care about

53:14.220 --> 53:17.660
something like rigor, with the same sense of satisfaction that comes from looking over

53:17.660 --> 53:21.340
a piece and saying, yes, I can officially check this off.

53:21.340 --> 53:24.860
That's something that feels like it's achievable when you're looking for a slight cultural

53:24.860 --> 53:30.900
shift, whereas fuzzier descriptions like we need to do better just aren't going to apply.

53:30.900 --> 53:34.420
So with that, I'd like to thank you all for coming.

53:34.420 --> 53:39.420
And thank you.

53:39.420 --> 53:50.420
Well, thank you, Grant.

53:50.420 --> 53:52.460
That was a lot of fun.

53:52.460 --> 53:59.540
For those of us like myself who grew up in a time when colored chalk was considered innovative,

53:59.540 --> 54:06.820
this was a very refreshing and eye-opening look at the ways that new ideas and technologies

54:06.860 --> 54:09.580
can help inform our work.

54:09.580 --> 54:15.980
And I think the age of digital textbooks and other kinds of interactive things that combine

54:15.980 --> 54:21.780
some of the elements you're talking about are going to offer some very exciting opportunities.

54:21.780 --> 54:23.900
We do have a little time for questions.

54:23.900 --> 54:29.820
We have a couple of microphones in the aisles, and I would invite you to line up.

54:29.820 --> 54:31.420
There are come to those microphones.

54:31.420 --> 54:35.100
If you'd like to ask a question, I think, Grant, you're up for that, right?

54:35.100 --> 54:36.100
Absolutely.

54:36.540 --> 54:40.580
I'd love to answer any questions, and I'll stick around outside of the ballroom afterwards

54:40.580 --> 54:43.020
if people want to come say hello.

54:43.020 --> 54:46.700
I'm not sure what the protocol here is, but let's say whoever is standing there at the

54:46.700 --> 54:47.700
mic first.

54:47.700 --> 54:48.700
Hi.

54:48.700 --> 54:56.060
I just wanted to ask you about in sort of exploring this idea of presenting data first

54:56.060 --> 55:00.500
and like this concrete information before getting to abstraction, do you have any thoughts

55:00.500 --> 55:06.460
on sort of in that process teaching students that you're not always going to see it, you're

55:06.460 --> 55:10.420
not always going to see it the first time, and like getting students comfortable with

55:10.420 --> 55:15.940
the idea that math can be hard, and this is an exploratory process that isn't necessarily

55:15.940 --> 55:19.140
targeted at getting to the abstraction first thing?

55:19.140 --> 55:24.700
Yeah, I think that's such a good point that even if the back of the mind goal of the exposer

55:24.700 --> 55:30.060
is that you've set up this stage so very carefully that surely anyone will follow up to the conclusion

55:30.100 --> 55:34.860
setting the expectations with everyone that like epiphany is very rare and discovery is

55:34.860 --> 55:39.180
something to be cherished, and if it was something that could happen all the time, it wouldn't

55:39.180 --> 55:41.580
be as lovely as it is.

55:41.580 --> 55:46.140
I'm not sure of the best ways to do that other than saying it in words and just kind of reassuring

55:46.140 --> 55:50.700
now and then like, hey, it's okay if you don't see this yet, or maybe holding off from a

55:50.700 --> 55:57.220
temptation to use phrases like obviously or like clearly and things like, but it's an

55:57.220 --> 55:59.540
important point to bring up, I appreciate that.

56:00.140 --> 56:01.100
On the right side here.

56:04.740 --> 56:09.740
Yeah, so there's a phrase that I've heard a couple of times, which is when teaching

56:09.740 --> 56:12.860
Matthews to teach the truth, nothing but the truth, but never the whole truth.

56:13.860 --> 56:20.300
How do you decide at what point, especially if you're teaching younger students, whatever

56:20.300 --> 56:26.980
that means, where it's good to give intuition rather than full rigor, how do you decide at

56:27.020 --> 56:29.420
which point to no longer be rigorous?

56:29.780 --> 56:30.580
That's a great question.

56:30.580 --> 56:36.100
I think I think you can always be honest about when you're being hand wavy.

56:36.860 --> 56:40.740
You know, Feynman was especially good at this with the Feynman lectures.

56:40.740 --> 56:44.540
I know because like physics is an exercise of constantly lying to people less and less over

56:44.540 --> 56:45.740
the course of their education.

56:46.140 --> 56:50.140
And he did a good job of like calling out the lies as they took place saying this is a

56:50.140 --> 56:51.300
simplifying assumption.

56:51.660 --> 56:53.060
And I don't think it takes that long.

56:53.060 --> 56:57.860
And so you can maybe tip your hat to the fact that there might be certain exceptions in

56:57.860 --> 56:58.700
certain cases.

57:00.100 --> 57:05.860
Or to the extent that's possible, you know, you you try to limit the scope of what you're

57:05.860 --> 57:10.060
saying such that if there is more complexity outside of it, you're just crystal clear about

57:10.060 --> 57:11.340
the setup as you go in.

57:11.820 --> 57:15.660
One other brief thought you said, you know, teach the truth and nothing but the truth.

57:16.060 --> 57:20.860
One direction I thought you were going with that was like, when is it fruitful to have

57:20.860 --> 57:24.820
little falsehoods through the lesson with it?

57:24.820 --> 57:30.460
I think one one form of exposition that is potentially really nice.

57:30.460 --> 57:38.340
And the friend of mine gave a name to it of discovery fiction is to try to map out a sequence

57:38.340 --> 57:42.740
of events that could lead to the discovery of a certain topic doesn't have to match the

57:42.740 --> 57:44.540
actual history of how something was discovered.

57:44.740 --> 57:47.860
But often the shape of it is that you come up with an idea that's just flawed.

57:48.260 --> 57:50.140
And then you try to fix it a little bit and fix that flaw.

57:50.140 --> 57:52.260
And then that has another flaw and then you fix it a little bit.

57:52.460 --> 57:53.340
And then that has a flaw.

57:54.100 --> 57:58.380
And as you proceed like this, sometimes it does a good job motivating why very seemingly

57:58.380 --> 58:01.340
arbitrary constructs are put in place to solve a certain problem.

58:01.700 --> 58:06.340
And the funny thing about that process is that through most of the lesson, you're like,

58:06.340 --> 58:11.700
you're describing something that is wrong or something that's not actually useful in the

58:11.700 --> 58:16.340
sense that the construct that's sitting in state in that moment isn't ever going to be

58:16.340 --> 58:16.740
used.

58:16.740 --> 58:18.660
It's just an intermediate step along the way.

58:18.900 --> 58:23.060
So I think trying to adhere too much to making sure that at every single step along the way,

58:23.340 --> 58:27.900
the objects that you're dealing with really work or the statements are fully true.

58:28.860 --> 58:33.900
You know, it's not always helpful to be constrained like that, assuming that you're very honest

58:33.900 --> 58:40.140
with the reader or the audience about where those falsehoods are and why and how they need

58:40.140 --> 58:40.900
to be corrected.

58:41.700 --> 58:42.060
All right.

58:42.220 --> 58:43.460
Other question on the left.

58:43.860 --> 58:44.140
Yeah.

58:44.140 --> 58:48.580
So suppose you have somebody you want to convey some kind of cool fact.

58:48.580 --> 58:49.260
Do you want to talk about?

58:49.420 --> 58:53.820
So I'm sure this is part of your process, but I didn't see it as one of your checks or one

58:53.820 --> 58:54.300
of your items.

58:54.300 --> 58:56.420
So I'm wondering like where this comes in the process.

58:56.420 --> 58:57.780
I mean, presumably has to be early on.

58:57.780 --> 59:01.220
But the idea of what is the right way to think about this?

59:01.220 --> 59:04.580
I mean, this has to be before planning the whole video because you have to decide like, I want

59:04.580 --> 59:05.140
to get to here.

59:05.260 --> 59:06.020
What is the route?

59:06.020 --> 59:10.300
How much time do you spend thinking about what is the right way to think about the final

59:10.300 --> 59:10.700
thing?

59:10.700 --> 59:14.300
And do you actually have that as one of your checks items that you didn't list?

59:14.380 --> 59:18.540
Yeah, I guess I exist in such a fortuitous situation where I choose

59:18.540 --> 59:22.100
the things that I teach, which is not always the case.

59:22.380 --> 59:25.940
And so I get to do this really luxurious thing where I just ambitiously learn about a lot

59:25.940 --> 59:29.500
of stuff and it's only it only ever bubbles to the point of wanting to make a video about

59:29.500 --> 59:34.220
it when it feels like there's that cool thing to show, which is often a slightly different

59:34.220 --> 59:36.420
perspective or something that was at least different to me.

59:37.460 --> 59:40.980
And so in a lot of ways, it's like, it's the zeroth law on that list, right?

59:40.980 --> 59:42.540
It's the thing that makes it get there.

59:42.940 --> 59:47.660
Now, the challenge mode question is suppose you don't live such a luxurious existence and

59:47.700 --> 59:51.140
instead you have an explicit set of things that you're supposed to teach.

59:51.580 --> 59:56.700
You know, I don't think there is like the right way to view it necessarily.

59:56.700 --> 01:00:01.780
But what I have found is, like I said, I really like to play around with visualizations of

01:00:01.780 --> 01:00:06.700
stuff, sometimes just doing a sort of brain dead thing to take the important formula and

01:00:06.700 --> 01:00:11.740
just slowly unpack what each part looks like has been like more fruitful than I would have

01:00:11.740 --> 01:00:12.340
expected.

01:00:12.620 --> 01:00:16.820
So one topic that in a certain sense, I didn't choose to make it.

01:00:16.820 --> 01:00:19.980
Just a lot of people were requesting it was 48 transforms.

01:00:20.020 --> 01:00:22.500
I'm like, I don't have anything to say about 48 transforms.

01:00:23.620 --> 01:00:25.860
But there was a lot of requests and I'm like, OK, what can we say here?

01:00:26.300 --> 01:00:30.140
And honestly, the video I made, it was just, I like look at the definition of it.

01:00:30.140 --> 01:00:31.300
And I started the innermost part.

01:00:31.300 --> 01:00:32.380
I'm like, how would you draw this?

01:00:32.420 --> 01:00:33.820
OK, how would you draw how these relate?

01:00:33.860 --> 01:00:34.740
OK, how would you draw these?

01:00:34.860 --> 01:00:36.700
Now that we have this drawing, how would you interpret it?

01:00:36.980 --> 01:00:39.100
How does that drawing change as you tweak this parameter?

01:00:39.860 --> 01:00:42.420
And kind of literally coding it up along the way.

01:00:42.420 --> 01:00:43.340
But I don't think you have to.

01:00:43.340 --> 01:00:44.980
I think it could have just been a whiteboard sketch.

01:00:45.940 --> 01:00:48.860
And the video ended up really resonating with people.

01:00:49.100 --> 01:00:53.860
And I think it was just a nice lesson for me that there didn't have to be a priori,

01:00:53.860 --> 01:00:58.020
some great aha that it was had, that sometimes just the seemingly brain-dead

01:00:58.020 --> 01:01:02.860
thing where you go step by step with this strong requirement of having an image

01:01:02.860 --> 01:01:08.020
in the head for what each part means goes farther than a lot of people might appreciate.

01:01:08.380 --> 01:01:12.500
Now, it can only be done on the important formulas because it's such a time-consuming

01:01:12.860 --> 01:01:16.340
process that you wouldn't want for every single thing that comes up in a given

01:01:16.340 --> 01:01:18.300
lecture to be like, oh, and how do we visualize this?

01:01:18.300 --> 01:01:19.140
How do we visualize this?

01:01:19.140 --> 01:01:23.140
You would just never get anywhere, not just in that lecture, but in the whole course.

01:01:23.300 --> 01:01:26.900
But if you're judicious about which parts deserve that level of deep dive,

01:01:27.820 --> 01:01:29.900
I actually think it's kind of a fruitful exercise.

01:01:29.900 --> 01:01:33.340
And whatever topic is maybe sitting in the back of your mind when you ask the question,

01:01:33.340 --> 01:01:37.420
it's like maybe a fun exercise to sit down and go from the inside out saying,

01:01:38.460 --> 01:01:41.820
just what would you draw if you had to communicate non-linguistically with someone

01:01:42.100 --> 01:01:45.060
to convey the idea over here?

01:01:46.180 --> 01:01:46.540
Hi, Grant.

01:01:46.540 --> 01:01:47.580
Thanks so much for the talk.

01:01:47.580 --> 01:01:49.620
It's very enjoyable and enlightening.

01:01:51.100 --> 01:01:56.900
My question is how you think that this sort of pedagogy checklist is influenced

01:01:56.900 --> 01:02:02.180
by students' desire to learn, because fortunately, you know, speaking of luxury,

01:02:02.180 --> 01:02:04.900
I think it's fair to say that you're in a position where most of the people

01:02:04.900 --> 01:02:08.460
that you get to teach nowadays are people who are there on purpose and they want to be.

01:02:09.460 --> 01:02:13.180
But we've all had the experience of having to teach students

01:02:13.180 --> 01:02:15.420
who really don't want to learn what you're trying to teach them.

01:02:16.380 --> 01:02:23.420
So how do you think the checklist can maybe be modified in consideration of the fact

01:02:23.420 --> 01:02:28.020
that a lot of the time in a university setting or especially in a primary

01:02:28.020 --> 01:02:31.260
or secondary school setting, there's going to be quite a few students

01:02:31.260 --> 01:02:33.900
who really are not interested in learning what you want to teach them?

01:02:34.140 --> 01:02:35.020
Such a good question.

01:02:36.020 --> 01:02:42.100
I mean, do any of you listen to the podcast An Opinionated History of Math, by chance?

01:02:42.900 --> 01:02:44.100
No, oh, you'll love it.

01:02:44.500 --> 01:02:45.340
It's one of my favorites.

01:02:45.340 --> 01:02:47.860
It's so obscure and like niche, but it's so delightful.

01:02:48.340 --> 01:02:51.780
But the author of it has on his website this little manifesto about teaching

01:02:52.020 --> 01:02:53.900
and he lists out like the axioms of learning.

01:02:54.140 --> 01:02:57.740
And one of his axioms of learning is essentially your point.

01:02:57.740 --> 01:03:00.540
Like people are not, how does he phrase it?

01:03:00.540 --> 01:03:01.980
He's so much more articulate than I am.

01:03:02.220 --> 01:03:06.380
But it's essentially, in order for someone to actually learn,

01:03:06.380 --> 01:03:07.980
they have to want to learn ahead of time.

01:03:09.300 --> 01:03:10.980
And so you're right, I'm in a luxurious position.

01:03:11.180 --> 01:03:14.580
Although, you know, it is the case that like every YouTuber thinks about,

01:03:14.580 --> 01:03:17.620
how do you bring someone into the topic if they might not have been thinking about it?

01:03:17.940 --> 01:03:21.300
And a couple of the standard things for this, like you try to appeal to a thing

01:03:21.300 --> 01:03:25.780
that interested them before they even walked in the room

01:03:25.780 --> 01:03:27.140
or before they clicked on the video.

01:03:28.540 --> 01:03:29.620
A loose example here.

01:03:30.220 --> 01:03:33.100
I'm not going to claim that things like this will always apply in the classroom,

01:03:33.100 --> 01:03:35.980
but I think maybe some examples do and it's worth inviting.

01:03:37.460 --> 01:03:40.460
I guess last year now, I made this video about Wordle,

01:03:40.740 --> 01:03:43.900
which was really on one hand, is jumping on a hype train

01:03:43.900 --> 01:03:46.340
because nothing was more popular on the internet than Wordle.

01:03:46.700 --> 01:03:48.940
But it was an excuse to teach information theory.

01:03:50.260 --> 01:03:54.980
And I can definitively say it reached more people than it would have

01:03:54.980 --> 01:03:57.860
if I had said I want to do a lesson about information theory.

01:03:58.860 --> 01:04:00.380
And I also think to good effect.

01:04:00.380 --> 01:04:02.660
There was one person who told me that it helped him get a job

01:04:02.660 --> 01:04:05.340
because there was an interview that he did where a question about Shannon

01:04:06.340 --> 01:04:08.860
entropy came up and like he had freshly watched the video.

01:04:09.300 --> 01:04:10.660
He probably would have gotten the job anyway,

01:04:10.660 --> 01:04:12.180
but I'll take all the credit I can get here.

01:04:12.540 --> 01:04:15.300
But something like that was, I think, you know,

01:04:16.180 --> 01:04:17.540
maybe a very special example,

01:04:17.540 --> 01:04:20.380
but there's probably a lot of different cases where you can find some connection

01:04:20.380 --> 01:04:22.300
to a thing that maybe isn't in the zeitgeist,

01:04:22.300 --> 01:04:25.220
but is of a pre-existing interest to the students.

01:04:25.940 --> 01:04:28.860
And just letting yourself take a little bit of time at the start of a class

01:04:28.860 --> 01:04:31.700
to let that be a motivating example might go a long way.

01:04:32.140 --> 01:04:35.980
The other thing I really do think clarity motivates.

01:04:36.060 --> 01:04:38.980
Like on the one hand, yes, it is very helpful to have someone

01:04:38.980 --> 01:04:41.580
who's already interested in learning and they sit there and they're

01:04:42.940 --> 01:04:45.420
they're willing to absorb whatever whatever you're going to give them,

01:04:45.420 --> 01:04:46.740
regardless of the clarity.

01:04:46.740 --> 01:04:50.740
But I also think if you if you take the time to have something

01:04:50.740 --> 01:04:53.340
like a compelling diagram to really illustrate what's going on,

01:04:53.740 --> 01:04:57.340
that is something that doesn't just feed pre-existing interest,

01:04:57.340 --> 01:04:59.460
but it can generate interest in the first place.

01:05:00.100 --> 01:05:03.260
And there's a lot of people who've told me that that was the thing

01:05:03.260 --> 01:05:05.180
about the channel that got them sucked in,

01:05:05.180 --> 01:05:07.260
that they hadn't cared about the channel at all before,

01:05:07.260 --> 01:05:10.860
but they started watching it because it elucidated something

01:05:10.860 --> 01:05:13.100
that was a class they were taking or something like that.

01:05:13.580 --> 01:05:16.340
And so they do feed into each other.

01:05:17.220 --> 01:05:21.180
But broadly speaking, I think what you bring up is another excellent example

01:05:21.180 --> 01:05:22.500
of something to sit on the checklist,

01:05:22.500 --> 01:05:25.500
which is essentially, do you have a compelling reason to believe

01:05:25.500 --> 01:05:28.620
that the audience sitting in front of you cares to listen to what you're saying?

